---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
import Sample from '../../components/Sample.astro';
---
<Base title="Warmth Is A Technical Decision" section={4}>
  <article class="prose">

    <SectionHeader
      n={4}
      title="Warmth Is A Technical Decision"
      meta="~500 words · 1 interactive sample"
    />

    <p>
      The decision to use <code>#fdf8f2</code> instead of <code>#ffffff</code>
      as a background color is not an aesthetic preference. It is a
      physiological one, and it has downstream consequences for every other
      color in the system.
    </p>

    <p>
      Pure white at high brightness produces what designers call "halation" —
      a slight blooming effect around dark text that increases eye strain
      over long reading sessions. The warm sandy tone of <code>--paper-0</code>
      reduces this by lowering the contrast ratio slightly and shifting the
      hue away from the cool end of the spectrum. The result is a background
      that recedes. The text advances. The reading is easier.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      The color system was deliberately named "paper" not "background."
      That word choice is doing architectural work — it establishes warmth
      as the default, not an override.
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      This matters architecturally because it inverts the usual cascade.
      Most design systems start with white and add warmth as an exception
      — a <code>warm-background</code> variant of a default cold surface.
      This system starts from paper. White, if it appears at all, is the
      exception. The implication is that every component is warm by default.
      Warmth doesn't need to be opt-in.
    </p>

    <Sample label="Interactive sample — warm vs. cold palette">
      <div>
        <div style="display: flex; gap: 8px; margin-bottom: 16px;">
          <button
            id="s4-warm-btn"
            onclick="s4Switch('warm')"
            style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; background: #fdf3e8; border: 0.5px solid #e8c9a0; color: #8b6345; border-radius: 6px; padding: 5px 12px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500;"
          >Paper (warm)</button>
          <button
            id="s4-cold-btn"
            onclick="s4Switch('cold')"
            style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; background: #f0f0f0; border: 0.5px solid #ddd; color: #555; border-radius: 6px; padding: 5px 12px; cursor: pointer;"
          >White (cold)</button>
        </div>

        <div
          id="s4-preview"
          style="
            border-radius: 8px;
            padding: 20px 24px;
            transition: background 480ms cubic-bezier(.4,0,.2,1), border-color 480ms cubic-bezier(.4,0,.2,1);
            background: #fdf8f2;
            border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc;
          "
        >
          <div id="s4-title" style="font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 400; margin-bottom: 6px; transition: color 480ms;">
            How the palette breathes
          </div>
          <div id="s4-body" style="font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; transition: color 480ms;">
            Body copy on a warm surface. The contrast is intentional — not harsh,
            not soft enough to be inaccessible. The eye rests naturally here.
          </div>
          <div id="s4-meta" style="font-size: 12px; font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; transition: color 480ms;">
            Metadata · captions · timestamps
          </div>
        </div>

        <div id="s4-note" style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 11px; font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; color: #a08060; letter-spacing: 0.04em; text-transform: uppercase;">
          Currently: paper — warm by default
        </div>
      </div>
      <script>
        (function() {
          const themes = {
            warm: {
              bg: '#fdf8f2', border: '#e4d9cc',
              title: '#2d1f0e', body: '#4a3728', meta: '#a08060',
              note: 'Currently: paper — warm by default'
            },
            cold: {
              bg: '#ffffff', border: '#e0e0e0',
              title: '#111111', body: '#333333', meta: '#888888',
              note: 'Currently: white — cold default'
            }
          };
          function s4Switch(mode) {
            const t = themes[mode];
            const preview = document.getElementById('s4-preview');
            const title   = document.getElementById('s4-title');
            const body    = document.getElementById('s4-body');
            const meta    = document.getElementById('s4-meta');
            const note    = document.getElementById('s4-note');
            if (!preview) return;
            preview.style.background   = t.bg;
            preview.style.borderColor  = t.border;
            if (title) title.style.color = t.title;
            if (body)  body.style.color  = t.body;
            if (meta)  meta.style.color  = t.meta;
            if (note)  note.textContent  = t.note;
          }
          window.s4Switch = s4Switch;
        })();
      </script>
    </Sample>

    <h2>Serif body type reinforces the right mode</h2>

    <p>
      The typeface choice is part of the same argument. Lora is a
      reading serif — designed for sustained on-screen reading, with
      letterforms that stay comfortable across body copy scales. It signals: this is for reading, not
      scanning. In contrast, sans-serif typefaces have evolved alongside
      digital UI — they're optimized for labels, buttons, navigation items.
      Using a sans for body copy imports those associations.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="Naming matters">
      Variable names encode intent. <code>--paper-0</code> signals that this
      is a surface material with texture and history. <code>--background-primary</code>
      signals that this is a configurable default. These are not the same concept.
      The name you give a token is a promise about how it should be used.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      When the typeface, color palette, and naming conventions all point in
      the same direction — warmth, reading, presence — the system becomes
      self-documenting. A designer new to the codebase doesn't need a style
      guide to understand why <code>--font-sans</code> goes on labels.
      The contrast with <code>--font-serif</code> carries the explanation.
    </p>

  </article>
</Base>
